			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Sharing Trees and Contextual Information: Re-imagining Forwarding in Attribute Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/LucasKramer.html">Lucas Kramer</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623520">10.1145/3623476.3623520</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is a technique within the attribute-grammar meta-language paradigm for structuring and reusing semantic computations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Forwarding and contextual information sharing primarily concern static analyses such as name resolution and type checking.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The work emphasizes modular feature extensions by translating new features to a core while sharing analysis results.
</li></ul></li></ul>
